"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675561","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>Under the Working Protocol between the Government and the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs (ACMD), “Ministers will look to provide a decision on all ACMD recommendations, and to publish a response within 3 months of receipt”. The Government is working towards responding to ACMD within this timeframe.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-24T12:04:05.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675561/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675561/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-19","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for the Government's response to the report by the Advisory Council on the misuse of drugs, reducing opioid-related deaths in the UK, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","60861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675562","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>I am sorry, but this information would only be available at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-30T11:26:30.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675562/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675562/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","UK Visas and Immigration: Judicial Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much UK Visas and Immigration paid out in costs in respect of judicial reviews of (a) deportation orders and (b) other immigration decisions in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","60869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675563","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Conflict Stability and Security Fund is a cross Whitehall fund. The Home Office contribution to that Fund is contained in the written evidence provided to the Joint Committee on the National Security Strategy at this link.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/national-security-strategy-committee/conflict-stability-and-security-fund/written/40690.html" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/national-security-strategy-committee/conflict-stability-and-security-fund/written/40690.html</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-25T16:48:34.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675563/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675563/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Home Office: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what projects by (a) name and (b) value her Department funded from the Conflict Stabilisation and Security Fund; and which of those projects were categorised as contributing towards Overseas Development Aid.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","60808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675564","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Home Office has obligations under the Data Protection Act (DPA) 1998 and in law generally to protect personal data. Therefore, the Home Office neither confirms nor denies by virtue of section 40(5) of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 whether it holds any information relevant to your question. This should not be taken as confirmation that any information is held.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T13:35:55.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675564/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675564/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Salva Kiir Mayardit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Salva Kiir Mayardit, President of South Sudan, holds (a) British citizenship and (b) a current UK passort.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","60809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675565","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The number of travel documents granted is available in the TD_01: Travel Documents, Applications Raised and Despatched tab of the quarterly Asylum Transparency Data Tables, which are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T15:50:01.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675565/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675565/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for stateless person travel documents have been made in each year since 2009-10; and how many of those applications were (a) accepted and (b) rejected.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675566","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>Information on the numbers of grants, refusals, withdrawals and lapsed cases for Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#visas</p><p> </p><p>Information on the numbers of admissions on Tier 1 (Investor) visas is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table ad_02_q (admissions data tables), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#admissions</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60882 ; 60885","2017-01-27T09:42:16.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675566/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675566/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for Tier 1 (Investor) visas have been refused in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","60883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675567","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The table below shows the number of disclosure applications which contained approved information from local police forces in each financial year since 2002, and the proportion of all disclosure applications this represents.</p><p>The Protection of Freedoms Act 2012 introduced a more rigorous test for relevancy on 10 September 2012. This changed the test for police disclosure to ensure that the disclosure of information was more effectively targeted at clear safeguarding risks. It also introduced a statutory code of practice for police to use when deciding what information to disclose.</p><p>Further requirements of the Act were introduced with the creation of the Disclosure and Barring Service on 1 December 2012.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Total disclosures despatched containing approved information</p></td><td><p>Total disclosures despatched</p></td><td><p>Proportion of total applications</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002/03</p></td><td><p>6,317</p></td><td><p>1,437,348</p></td><td><p>0.44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003/04</p></td><td><p>10,158</p></td><td><p>2,287,522</p></td><td><p>0.44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>11,160</p></td><td><p>2,432,933</p></td><td><p>0.46%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>15,449</p></td><td><p>2,776,378</p></td><td><p>0.56%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>15,693</p></td><td><p>3,278,031</p></td><td><p>0.48%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>17,362</p></td><td><p>3,323,402</p></td><td><p>0.52%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>20,797</p></td><td><p>3,856,583</p></td><td><p>0.54%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>24,554</p></td><td><p>4,301,313</p></td><td><p>0.57%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>23,882</p></td><td><p>4,312,533</p></td><td><p>0.55%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>16,296</p></td><td><p>4,074,241</p></td><td><p>0.40%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2012 to 31 Nov 2012[1]</p></td><td><p>8,219</p></td><td><p>2,842,832</p></td><td><p>0.29%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 Dec 2012 to 31 March 2013[2]</p></td><td><p>3,265</p></td><td><p>1,223,773</p></td><td><p>0.27%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>9,626</p></td><td><p>3,948,733</p></td><td><p>0.24%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>9,899</p></td><td><p>4,111,856</p></td><td><p>0.24%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>9,650</p></td><td><p>4,214,541</p></td><td><p>0.23%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17 to 31/12/16</p></td><td><p>7,120</p></td><td><p>3,258,103</p></td><td><p>0.22%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>[1] Figures prior to Disclosure and Barring Service creation to meet the requirements under Protection of Freedoms Act 2012</p><p>[2] Figures post Disclosure and Barring Service creation to meet the requirements under Protection of Freedoms Act 2012.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T13:55:17.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675567/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675567/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions police forces have provided additional information for criminal records checks in each financial year (a) before and (b) since the passage of the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012; and what proportion of total applications that number represents.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675568","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>The Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse is independent of Government. Matters relating to staffing are for the Inquiry.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","60945","2017-01-27T09:33:05.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675568/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675568/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have worked for the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse since that inquiry was established; and how many such people have received (a) standard, (b) enhanced and (c) enhanced with barred list checks by the Disclosure and Barring Service.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675569","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Home Office Stateless policy is designed to assist those who do not qualify for protection but are unable to return to the country of their former habitual residence because they are stateless and would not be admitted to any other country. The requirements are set out in the Immigration Rules and reflect our obligations under the 1954 UN Convention relating to the status of stateless persons.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office has released information on Stateless applications and decisions made in the response to previous parliamentary questions 50073, 50074 and 50075:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-25/50073/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-25/50073/</a></p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Home Office regularly shares information with UNHCR, relating to stateless applications and decisions made. The information provided is published by UNHCR, in regular trend reports, the latest published report by UNHCR on mid year trends June 2015 can be found at link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.unhcr.org/uk/statistics/unhcrstats/56701b969/mid-year-trends-june-2015.html%20" target="_blank">http://www.unhcr.org/uk/statistics/unhcrstats/56701b969/mid-year-trends-june-2015.html </a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60943","2017-01-24T15:52:16.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675569/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675569/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications to renew the right to stay in the UK as a stateless person were made by people who previously had the right to remain as a stateless person in each year since 2009-10; and how many of those applications were (a) accepted and (b) rejected.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675570","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>For the period of 2010 I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given on 5 January 2016, UIN 20698. For the period of 2014 I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given on 5 January 2016, UIN 20698.</p><p>Information relating to the reasons and the harm type under which each person was so placed cannot be provided without incurring disproportionate costs.</p><p>Tables 1 and 2 show the number of people who were added to the Children’s and Adults’ Barred Lists for the years 2015 and 2016.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Children’s Barred List</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1. Autobar without<br>representations</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2. Autobar with<br>representations</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3. Discretionary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>1334</p></td><td><p>1421</p></td><td><p>84</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2016</p></td><td><p>1302</p></td><td><p>1391</p></td><td><p>107</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Table 2: Adults’ Barred List</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1. Autobar without<br>representations</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2. Autobar with<br>representations</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3. Discretionary</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>1036</p></td><td><p>283</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2016</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>953</p></td><td><p>258</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","60830","2017-01-27T14:47:39.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675570/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675570/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 7 August 2014 to Question 205989, on vetting and the Disclosure and Barring Service, if she will provide those statistics for (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675571","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>Decisions on the allocation of the Metropolitan Police’s resources are a matter for Chief Officers, in association with the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime (MOPAC). The police have the resources to do their important work.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided a fair provisional funding deal for 2017/18. It provides stable funding for the police and enables essential policing reform and transformation to go further and faster so that we help the vulnerable, cut crime and support our communities.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the average time for the police to visit a burglary scene is not captured centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60924","2017-01-25T15:28:56.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675571/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675571/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Burglary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken was for police to visit a burglary scene following a reported burglary in each police force area in England and Wales in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675572","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>Decisions on the allocation of the Metropolitan Police’s resources are a matter for Chief Officers, in association with the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime (MOPAC). The police have the resources to do their important work.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided a fair provisional funding deal for 2017/18. It provides stable funding for the police and enables essential policing reform and transformation to go further and faster so that we help the vulnerable, cut crime and support our communities.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the average time for the police to visit a burglary scene is not captured centrally by the Home Office.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60925","2017-01-25T15:28:56.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675572/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675572/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Burglary: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of resources to attend to reported burglaries in (a) London and (b) West Ham constituency on 28 December 2016.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675573","Home Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The table below shows the number of appeals relating to England, Wales and Northern Ireland that are upheld and result in the person being removed from one or more of the barred lists. This table also includes cases where an appellant has agreed to withdraw an appeal, following their removal from a list or lists by the Disclosure and Barring Service using its review powers. The data does not break down to allow comparison between the children’s and adults barred lists.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Calendar Years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total number of appeals concluded by the Upper Tribunal</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Appeals upheld</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Appeals not upheld</strong> <strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data on appeals before 2015 is not available without incurring disproportionate costs.</p><p>In addition to appeals, there are two other ways for people to make representations for removal from the barred lists. The Disclosure and Barring Service cannot provide data on late representations or barring reviews without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-07T13:28:21.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675573/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675573/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people made representations to the (a) Disclosure and Barring Service and (b) Independent Safeguarding Authority to remove their names from the (i) children's and (ii) adult's barred list in each year since 2009-10; and what proportion of those representations were (A) successful and (B) unsuccessful.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675574","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Home Office Stateless policy is designed to assist those who do not qualify for protection but are unable to return to the country of their former habitual residence because they are stateless and would not be admitted to any other country. The requirements are set out in the Immigration Rules and reflect our obligations under the 1954 UN Convention relating to the status of stateless persons.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office has released information on Stateless applications and decisions made in the response to previous parliamentary questions 50073, 50074 and 50075:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-25/50073/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-10-25/50073/</a></p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Home Office regularly shares information with UNHCR, relating to stateless applications and decisions made. The information provided is published by UNHCR, in regular trend reports, the latest published report by UNHCR on mid year trends June 2015 can be found at link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.unhcr.org/uk/statistics/unhcrstats/56701b969/mid-year-trends-june-2015.html%20" target="_blank">http://www.unhcr.org/uk/statistics/unhcrstats/56701b969/mid-year-trends-june-2015.html </a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60936","2017-01-24T15:52:17.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675574/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675574/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications to stay in the UK as a stateless person were made in each year since 2009-10; and how many of those applications were (a) accepted and (b) rejected.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675575","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>The proportion of Tier 1 Investors who arrived in the UK who later applied to settle; and the proportion of those later applications that were successful cannot be obtained without exceeding proportionate cost limits</p><p><br> The number of Tier 1 (Investor) settlement application granted are publish and are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/settlement#data-tables" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/settlement#data-tables</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-27T09:43:37.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675575/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675575/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of people who arrive in the UK on Tier 1 (Investor) visas later apply to settle; and what proportion of those later applications is successful.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","60884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675576","Home Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The number of applications for barred list checks in the controlled activity category is listed in the table below for each financial year. The category was repealed by the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Applications Submitted</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Matches found against the Barred Lists</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-07T13:27:13.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675576/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675576/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many barred list checks were made for people in the controlled activity category in each year until that category was repealed by the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012; and how many of those checks (a) found and (b) did not find matches with the barred list. in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","60932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675577","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>Information on the numbers of grants, refusals, withdrawals and lapsed cases for Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#visas</p><p> </p><p>Information on the numbers of admissions on Tier 1 (Investor) visas is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table ad_02_q (admissions data tables), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#admissions</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60883 ; 60885","2017-01-27T09:42:16.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675577/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675577/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people arrived in the UK on Tier 1 (Investor) visas in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","60882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675578","Home Office","false","2017-01-27","<p>Information on the numbers of grants, refusals, withdrawals and lapsed cases for Tier 1 (Investor) visa applications is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table vi_01_q (visa data tables volume 1), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#visas</p><p> </p><p>Information on the numbers of admissions on Tier 1 (Investor) visas is published quarterly, latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016’, table ad_02_q (admissions data tables), available here: www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#admissions</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60882 ; 60883","2017-01-27T09:42:16.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675578/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675578/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-19","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people are in the UK having arrived on a Tier 1 (Investor) visa.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","60885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675579","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-24T12:05:52.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675579/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675579/answer","PQ60953 v.02.pdf","PQ60953 v.02.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Credit Card Fraud","UKSA Letter to Member - Credit Card Fraud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675579/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-19","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, in what year the Crime Survey for England and Wales first asked questions on (a) any form of cyber-enabled and (b) credit card fraud.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675580","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-26","<p>The UK does not possess a Joint Precision Airdrop System (JPADS) capability. Our assessment is that, although JPADS is relatively precise, the size and weight of the system and the risk risk of collateral damage are such that it is not generally suitable for use in a populated environment. We continue to work with allies and partners on potential options for delivering aid but the most effective means remains road deliveries of large quantities, organised by Humanitarian agencies and coordinated with authorities on the ground.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","60818","2017-01-26T16:10:10.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675580/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675580/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-19","Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the utility of the Joint Precision Aerial Delivery System for delivering humanitarian aid; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","60826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675581","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-26","<p>The UK does not possess a Joint Precision Airdrop System (JPADS) capability. Our assessment is that, although JPADS is relatively precise, the size and weight of the system and the risk risk of collateral damage are such that it is not generally suitable for use in a populated environment. We continue to work with allies and partners on potential options for delivering aid but the most effective means remains road deliveries of large quantities, organised by Humanitarian agencies and coordinated with authorities on the ground.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","60826","2017-01-26T16:10:09.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675581/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675581/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-19","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment the Government has made of using the Joint Precision Airdrop System to provide aid to besieged Syrian civilians.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","60818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675582","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-26","<p>The numbers related to absence due to mental illness for senior civil servants are so low that providing this information could potentially identify individuals.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-26T17:15:55.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675582/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675582/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-19","Department for International Development: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many senior civil servants in her Department were on a leave of absence from work due to mental illness in each month of each year since the Department's creation.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","60803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675583","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>In 2016, DFID was the second largest donor to the humanitarian crisis in North-East Nigeria. We are a major funder of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) which has been providing life-saving assistance to the displaced people in Rann. This assistance will continue. We are also a major funder of the United Nations Humanitarian Air Service (UNHAS) who (together with ICRC) provided emergency medical treatment and evacuation to those wounded in the bombing incident of 17 January 2017.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-24T16:51:14.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675583/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675583/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-19","Nigeria: Internally Displaced Persons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department plans to provide additional resources to the dispatched persons camp in Rann, North Eastern Nigeria as a result of the airstrike on that camp.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675584","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>During January to December 2016, Marie Stopes International (MSI) directly received £44.45 million from DFID through several programmes including: Urban Health for poor mothers in Bangladesh, Reducing Maternal Death Kenya, Family Planning Services Malawi, Reproductive Health Services Pakistan and Improving Reproductive and Maternal and New born health Sierra Leone.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-24T17:08:49.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675584/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/675584/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-19","Marie Stopes International","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much was paid from the public purse to Marie Stopes International in 2016; and how much of that total came from the international aid budget for expenditure overseas in 2016.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","60715"
